              <dl class="sources_row">
                <dt>Cautions</dt>
                <dd>
                  <p>Forest > 25% includes all types of forest be it plantations, primary forest, secondary forest or any other type of cover that has trees. Hence tree cover change does not equate deforestation. The change could be the result of harvesting of timber in plantations or replanting of palm oil trees.</p>

                  <p>In some cases tree cover loss between 2000 and 2012 appears in areas where there was no tree cover in 2000 according to the tree cover extent map. This is because Landsat did not register tree cover in areas that had very low tree cover density (e.g. <5%) in 2000, but the process used to detect tree cover loss between 2000 and 2012 was capable of detecting drops in tree cover at even the lowest densities (e.g. 0-5%). In these instances it appears as though tree cover loss occurred in areas without tree cover in the year 2000, when in fact there was tree cover in these areas, just at very low densities that were not detected by Landsat.</p>
                </dd>
              </dl>
