            <div class="source_summary">
              <h3 class="overview_title">Overview</h3>
              <p>This data set measures both area of tree cover loss and gain across the globe at 30 × 30 meter spatial resolution on an annual basis from 2001 to 2012.  However gain is only displayed as a 12 year cumulative layer.  The data were generated using multispectral satellite imagery from the <a href="http://landsat.usgs.gov/science_L7_cpf.php" target="_blank">Landsat 7 thematic mapper plus (ETM+)</a> sensor. Multiple Landsat 7 images were compiled in Google Earth Engine and the clear surface observations from these images were then assembled into a per pixel forest probability time series that was classified into either tree cover loss or no change. Tree cover loss was defined as “stand replacement disturbance,” or the complete removal of tree cover canopy at the Landsat pixel scale.  Forest gain was defined as the inverse of loss, or the establishment of tree canopy from non-forest state.  Both global forest loss and gain were related to tree cover density for climate domains, ecozones, and countries. Previously tested methods of high- (Quickbird) and medium- (Landsat) resolution satellite imagery interpretation for tree cover were used to delineate change and no change for training data and to determine the areas of tree cover loss and gain.</p>

