            <div class="source_summary">
              <h3 class="overview_title">Overview</h3>
              <p>The FORMA alerts data set uses an <a href="https://github.com/reddmetrics/forma-clj" target="_blank">algorithm</a> to analyze freely available satellite imagery products and other ancillary data to identify new areas of forest clearing in near real-time across the world’s <a href="http://wolfweb.unr.edu/~ldyer/classes/396/olsonetal.pdf" target="_blank">humid tropical forest biome</a>. The system analyzes data gathered daily by the <a href="http://modis.gsfc.nasa.gov/about/" target="_blank">MODIS</a> sensor, which operates on NASA’s Terra and Aqua satellites. The FORMA alerts system then detects pronounced changes in vegetation cover over time, as measured by the <a href="http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/Features/MeasuringVegetation/measuring_vegetation_2.php" target="_blank">Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI)</a>, a measure of vegetation greenness. These pronounced changes in vegetation cover are likely to be indicative of forest being cleared, burned, or defoliated.</p>

              <p>This algorithm produces alerts that indicate where forest clearing is statistically likely to have occurred within a 500 meter × 500 meter area. FORMA alerts only appear in areas where the probability of forest clearing is greater than or equal to 50.</p>

              <p>Upcoming upgrades to FORMA include improving the resolution to 250 meters × 250 meters, and expanding coverage to tropical dry forest and eventually to other biomes across the global scale.</p>

              <p class="credits"><strong>Citation:</strong><br />Hammer, Dan, Robin Kraft, and David Wheeler. 2013. “FORMA Alerts.” World Resources Institute and Center for Global Development. Accessed through Global Forest Watch on [date]. <a href="http://www.globalforestwatch.org" target="_blank">www.globalforestwatch.org</a>.</p>

