              </dl>
              <dl class="sources_row">
                <dt>Date of content</dt>
                <dd>2000</dd>
              </dl>
            </div>

            <div class="source_summary">
              <h3 class="overview_title">Overview</h3>
              <p>This data set shows the global percent tree cover for the year 2000 at 30 × 30 meter spatial resolution and covering all global lands except for Antarctica and a number of Arctic islands.  The extent data was generated using multispectral satellite imagery from the <a href="http://landsat.usgs.gov/" target="_blank">Landsat 7 thematic mapper plus (ETM+)</a> sensor, and all images were compiled in the Google Earth Engine. The clear surface observations from the thousands of images employed for the analysis were then assembled into a per pixel forest probability time series to classify tree cover. For the classification threshold of tree cover, trees were defined as all vegetation taller than 5 meters in height.</p>

              <p class="credits"><strong>Citation:</strong><br />Hansen, M. C., P. V. Potapov, R. Moore, M. Hancher, S. A. Turubanova, A. Tyukavina, D. Thau, S. V. Stehman, S. J. Goetz, T. R. Loveland, A. Kommareddy, A. Egorov, L. Chini, C. O. Justice, and J. R. G. Townshend. 2013. “High-Resolution Global Maps of 21st-Century Forest Cover Change.” Science 342 (15 November): 850–53.</p>

              <p class="credits"><strong>Suggested citation for data as displayed on GFW:</strong><br />Hansen, M. C., P. V. Potapov, R. Moore, M. Hancher, S. A. Turubanova, A. Tyukavina, D. Thau, S. V. Stehman, S. J. Goetz, T. R. Loveland, A. Kommareddy, A. Egorov, L. Chini, C. O. Justice, and J. R. G. Townshend. 2013. “Tree Cover Extent.” University of Maryland and Google. Accessed through Global Forest Watch on [date]. <a href="http://www.globalforestwatch.org" target="_blank">www.globalforestwatch.org</a>.</p>

